<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How is cocktail ABV calculated?", answer: "Cocktail ABV is the volume-weighted average ABV of all ingredients, then adjusted downward for the water added by ice melt during shaking or stirring. The pre-dilution ABV equals the sum of each ingredient volume times its ABV, divided by the total ingredient volume. After dilution the final ABV equals the pre-dilution ABV divided by 1 plus the dilution percentage." },
  { question: "How much dilution does shaking add?", answer: "Per Dave Arnold's Liquid Intelligence and other modern bar science references, hard shaking with cracked ice typically adds 25 to 30 percent dilution by volume in 10 to 15 seconds. Stirring with cubed ice adds about 20 to 25 percent dilution in 30 to 40 seconds. Building drinks on the rocks adds 5 to 15 percent depending on how long you take to drink them. Built drinks with no ice add zero dilution." },
  { question: "Why does dilution matter for cocktail ABV?", answer: "Dilution can drop the alcohol content of a cocktail by 20 to 30 percent. A martini stirred from 2 ounces of 40 percent gin and half an ounce of 18 percent vermouth has a pre-dilution ABV of 35.6 percent, but after stirring the final ABV is closer to 28 percent. Knowing the post-dilution ABV is essential for understanding how strong a drink actually is and for tracking standard drinks responsibly." },
  { question: "What is a US standard drink?", answer: "A US standard drink contains 14 grams of pure alcohol, which is the alcohol in roughly 12 ounces of 5 percent beer, 5 ounces of 12 percent wine, or 1.5 ounces of 40 percent spirit. The calculator converts the final cocktail volume and ABV into standard drinks so you can track consumption against guidelines from the CDC and dietary recommendations." },
  { question: "Does this work for batched cocktails?", answer: "Yes, exactly. For a batched cocktail you measure each ingredient by volume and treat the bottled or stored mix the same as a single drink. Just remember that batched cocktails do not get the same ice dilution as fresh-shaken individual servings, so most bartenders pre-dilute the batch with cold water to match the dilution they would expect from shaking." }
]) %>

